Kingdom":"Engleska, United Kingdom","Powderidge, Devon, England":"Devon, Engleska, United Kingdom","Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Engleska, United Kingdom"},"cs":{"about 1088–":"okolo 1088–Zesnulý","1088–Male":"1088–Zesnulý","1090–Male":"1090–Zesnulý","1092–Female":"1092–Zesnulá","1118–Male":"1118–Zesnulý","1058–Male":"1058–Zesnulý","1062–Female":"1062–Zesnulá","1080":"1080","1118":"1118","1090":"1090","1115":"1115","1058":"1058","1088":"1088","ABT 1118":"okolo 1118","1062":"1062","about 1088":"okolo 1088","1092":"1092","Powderidge,Devon,England":"Devon, Anglie, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"Anglie, United Kingdom","Powderidge, Devon, England":"Devon, Anglie, United Kingdom","Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"about 1088–":"omkring 1088–Afdød","1088–Male":"1088–Afdød","1090–Male":"1090–Afdød","1092–Female":"1092–Afdød","1118–Male":"1118–Afdød","1058–Male":"1058–Afdød","1062–Female":"1062–Afdød","1080":"1080","1118":"1118","1090":"1090","1115":"1115","1058":"1058","1088":"1088","ABT 1118":"omkring 1118","1062":"1062","about 1088":"omkring 1088","1092":"1092","Powderidge,Devon,England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","Powderidge, Devon, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 1088–":"circa 1088–Overleden","1088–Male":"1088–Overleden","1090–Male":"1090–Overleden","1092–Female":"1092–Overleden","1118–Male":"1118–Overleden","1058–Male":"1058–Overleden","1062–Female":"1062–Overleden","1080":"1080","1118":"1118","1090":"1090","1115":"1115","1058":"1058","1088":"1088","ABT 1118":"circa 1118","1062":"1062","about 1088":"circa 1088","1092":"1092","Powderidge,Devon,England":"Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Powderidge, Devon, England":"Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1088–":"about 1088–Deceased","1088–Male":"1088–Deceased","1090–Male":"1090–Deceased","1092–Female":"1092–Deceased","1118–Male":"1118–Deceased","1058–Male":"1058–Deceased","1062–Female":"1062–Deceased","1080":"1080","1118":"1118","1090":"1090","1115":"1115","1058":"1058","1088":"1088","ABT 1118":"about 1118","1062":"1062","about 1088":"about 1088","1092":"1092","Powderidge,Devon,England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","Powderidge, Devon, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Le","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Thanh, Hung, Minh, Dung, Tuan, Hai, Hoa, Thuy, Son, Anh, Long, Hoang.  Chinese Hong, Sang, Chi, Dong, Tong, Lai, Hang, Man, Han, Ho, Phoung, Chan.  Korean Tam, Phong, Nam, Thai, Tuong, Chung, Thach, Tinh, Manh, Tham, Uyen, Vang.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 樂, meaning ‘happiness’ in Chinese: from the first element of the personal name Le Fu (樂父), style name of Yan, son of the Duke Dai of Song (ruler of the state of Song, reigned 799–766  BC ). Yan's grandson Le Ju (樂莒) inherited Le (樂) as his surname.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 勒: (i) from the second element of the placename Shu-Le (疏勒), an ancient state (located in present-day Xinjiang Uyghur autonomous region) during the Western Han dynasty (206  BC –25  AD ). (ii) a surname near the Bohai Sea region during the Han dynasty (206  BC –220  AD ). (iii) a surname traced back to the Hun ethnic group in northern China during the Jin dynasty (265–420  AD )."],"variants":[{"name":"Yue","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese: Chi, Feng, Gang, Wei, Chun, Guo, Jin, Kin, Ping, Yan, Yun, Zhang, Chau, Du, Hau, Hung, My, Sau.","Chinese:","Mandarin form of the surname 岳 (or 嶽), meaning ‘high mountain’ in Chinese: traced back to Si Yue (四岳 or 四嶽), said to be the title of an official post in charge of sacrificial rituals on the site of famous mountains during the reign of the legendary Emperor Yao (<i>c.</i> 24th century  BC ) and Emperor Shun (<i>c.</i> 23rd century  BC )."]},{"name":"Lok","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Ping, Tat, Wing, Ying Lin, Chi Ming, Ching Wah, Chun, Chung Man, Han, Kam, Kam Tim, Kin.","Chinese: Cantonese form of the surname 樂, see   Le   1.","Chinese: Cantonese form of the surnames 陸, 鹿, 逯 and 禄, see   Lu   5 and (7-9)."]},{"name":"Li","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wei, Ming, Li, Jian, Hong, Yan, Ping, Jing, Yong, Ying, Hui, Jin, Min, Chung.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 李, meaning ‘plum’: (i) said to have been adopted in place of the Chinese surname 理 (also pronounced Li; meaning ‘rules’ in Chinese) by Li Zhen (利貞), son of an official called Li Zheng (理徵) in the late Shang dynasty (1600–1046  BC ). It is said that Li Zhen's father incurred the displeasure of King Zhou of Shang (died 1046  BC ) and Li Zhen fled to a wasteland area, where he survived on wild plums. After his return to civilization, he changed his surname to Li (李 ‘plum’), a word with the same pronunciation. The original surname, 理, is said to be from Li Guan (理官), the name of a post of officials in charge of legislation in ancient China. Li Er (李耳), also known as Lao Tzu or Lao Zi, traditionally regarded as the founder of Taoism, is believed to have been a descendant of Li Zhen. (ii) adopted as a surname by the Chi Li (叱李) family from the Xianbei ethnic group during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iii) in the early years of the Tang dynasty (618–907  AD ), sixteen high officials with different surnames were granted the surname Li (李), the surname of the royal family of the Tang dynasty, by Emperor Taizong of Tang (died 649  BC ), because of their contributions to the establishment of the Tang regime. (iv) the surname can also be traced back to several minority ethnic groups in ancient China.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 黎, meaning ‘black’ or ‘multitude’ in ancient Chinese: (i) from Li (黎), the name of an ancient state (located in Changzhi in Shanxi province) during the Shang dynasty (1600–1046  BC ), which was annexed in the Western Zhou dynasty (1046–771  BC ) and later granted to Fengshu, also known as Li Hou (黎侯, 'Marquis Li'). (ii) adopted as a surname by the Su Li (素黎) family, members of the Xianbei ethnic group, during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD )."]}]},{"name":"Moyne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  Norman, English: nickname from Old French  <i>moine</i>, Anglo-Norman French  <i>muine</i>,  <i>moingne</i> ‘monk’. Some of the following early bearers without the definite article could alternatively belong with (2).","2  English:  see  Moon   (1)."],"variants":[{"name":"Moin","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of <b>Moyne</b>, a nickname from Old French <i>moine</i>, Anglo-Norman French <i>muine</i>, <i>moingne</i> ‘monk’.","Muslim (mainly the Indian subcontinent): unexplained."]},{"name":"Moon","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Mohan  .","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Moyon in La Manche. Compare   Mounce  .","Americanized form of German   Mohn   or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]},{"name":"Moynan","meanings":["Irish: perhaps a diminutive of   Moyne   or a reduced form of   Moynihan  ."]},{"name":"Moine","meanings":["French: from <i>moine</i> ‘monk’, probably applied as an occupational name for a servant at a monastery or an ironic nickname for someone of monkish behavior or appearance. Compare   Lemoine  ."]},{"name":"Moynes","meanings":["English: variant of   Moyne   with post-medieval excrescent  <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Peter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name of the best-known of all Christ's apostles, traditionally regarded as the founder of the Christian Church. The name derives, via Latin, from Greek <i>petros</i> ‘stone, rock’. This is used as a translation of the Aramaic byname <i>Cephas</i>, given to the apostle  Simon  son of Jona, to distinguish him from another of the same name (  Simon Zelotes ). ‘When Jesus beheld him, he said, Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Peter Le Moyne was born about 1088, in Devon, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir William Le Moyne, was 32 and his mother, Mother Tilley, was 28. He married Maude Coffin in 1115, in Devon, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"about 1088–":"umbes 1088–Surnud","1088–Male":"1088–Surnud","1090–Male":"1090–Surnud","1092–Female":"1092–Surnud","1118–Male":"1118–Surnud","1058–Male":"1058–Surnud","1062–Female":"1062–Surnud","1080":"1080","1118":"1118","1090":"1090","1115":"1115","1058":"1058","1088":"1088","ABT 1118":"umbes 1118","1062":"1062","about 1088":"umbes 1088","1092":"1092","Powderidge,Devon,England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Powderidge, Devon, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1088–":"noin 1088–Kuollut","1088–Male":"1088–Kuollut","1090–Male":"1090–Kuollut","1092–Female":"1092–Kuollut","1118–Male":"1118–Kuollut","1058–Male":"1058–Kuollut","1062–Female":"1062–Kuollut","1080":"1080","1118":"1118","1090":"1090","1115":"11